I am a skilled psychologist from Yemen, I once drunk a cup of coffee mixed with the menstruation blood of a 26-year-old female, I actually spent the night in a coma due to physiological and spiritual intoxication, and during the coma, I had the most disturbing nightmares ever:-

1- Well, I know this might sound a bit odd and random, but I have dreamt of Zeus mating with a palm tree and begetting an ant that is capable of crawling on the edge of the Higgs Boson!

2- I once also dreamt of my mitochondria protesting to break free from my organelles , claiming that nature has enslaved them !

3- On that night of a full moon, I dreamt of Professor Noam Chomsky eating books and regurgitating the field of Modern Linguistics!

4- The funniest dream I ever had, was when I had a vision of a Neanderthal swallowing a whole apple, and it played ping-pong with his heart while passing down his oesophagus!

5- The most disgusting dream I ever had, was of a female's menstruation blood turning into jelly and been marketed by an Oompa Loompa as Halloween treats!

I regret not listening to mummy and staying away from "coffee-menstrual shots", now I have developed a neurological disorder!

Do you guys think that my dreams have any philosophical implications at all?

Given that I've been hearing my neurons conspiring to abandon the dwelling of my skull, things don't seem to be heading in the right direction, ever since!

Only very recently did I start exploring the country. To my astonishment, this country has so much to offer. SA is so prodigal of her natural gifts. It's a pity that I've wasted a good number of years thinking that SA is just a bunch of modern cities built amidst lifeless desert terrain. Now because photography is my hobby, even my life-long passion, I've been taking stunning landscape photos of the country wherever I go. When I share them with kith and kin back home and further afield, they all unanimously ask the same Q: Are you sure this is Saudi Arabia? It's interesting to discover first hand how reality can be startlingly such a far cry from pre-misconceptions.
